docs.lead_paragraph: Shares of the rental car company Avis Budget Group more than doubled on Tuesday, in a sudden and unexpected surge that recalled earlier trading manias in GameStop, AMC Entertainment and other so-called meme stocks. Bed Bath & Beyond, the retailer that attracted some interest during previous meme-stock episodes, also rose sharply in late trading.

headline.main: Meet the new meme stocks? Shares of Avis and Bed Bath & Beyond soar.

docs.abstract: Elliott talks about her new book, and Phoebe Robinson discusses “Please Don’t Sit on My Bed in Your Outside Clothes.”
docs.snippet: Elliott talks about her new book, and Phoebe Robinson discusses “Please Don’t Sit on My Bed in Your Outside Clothes.”
docs.lead_paragraph: In 2013, the front page of The New York Times devoted five straight days to the story of Dasani, an 11-year-old Black girl who lived in a homeless shelter in Brooklyn. Now, Andrea Elliott, the reporter of that series, has published her first book, “Invisible Child,” which tells the full story of Dasani and her family up to the present day. On this week’s podcast, Elliott discusses how she came to focus her reporting on Dasani.

docs.abstract: An antidote to earth-toned minimalism, Ellen Van Dusen’s designs suggest that children aren’t the only ones drawn to bold colors and shapes.
docs.snippet: An antidote to earth-toned minimalism, Ellen Van Dusen’s designs suggest that children aren’t the only ones drawn to bold colors and shapes.
docs.lead_paragraph: As a child, Ellen Van Dusen became fixated on the kinetic colors in the artist Ellsworth Kelly’s paintings, which she’d come upon during her frequent museum visits in Washington, D.C., where she grew up. She was puzzled by Kelly’s abstract minimalist works, several of which comprise flat, solid stretches of a single shade; “I was like, ‘It’s just a green canvas; what’s wrong with my brain?’” says the 35-year-old owner of the textiles and home-accessories brand Dusen Dusen. Such questions stuck with her when she was an undergraduate at Tufts, where she majored in a multidisciplinary mix of art history, neuroscience and visual anthropology. “I studied the visual process from different angles,” she says. “Neuroscience is where I focused on vision: how things come through the eye, how they’re processed through the brain and what evolutionarily draws the eye.” But she kept coming back to color.

headline.main: A Textile Designer Who Draws on Art History and Neuroscience

docs.abstract: Following a period of editing and rediscovery, austerity and abundance — and a wide range of objects — live side by side in this Bedford-Stuyvesant apartment.
docs.snippet: Following a period of editing and rediscovery, austerity and abundance — and a wide range of objects — live side by side in this Bedford-Stuyvesant apartment.
docs.lead_paragraph: AS A CHILD in Virginia, Michael Brown collected birds’ nests, stamps and mounted beetles and butterflies. By the age of 10, he had graduated to Goofus glass vases — cold-painted trinkets produced in the early 20th century that were often given as fairground prizes — and old-fashioned spectacle frames he’d find at local flea markets. His first job, at 18, was dressing windows at the Richmond department store Thalhimers, and on the weekends he began collecting antique furniture and curiosities, a habit that continued into adulthood, as he worked as an interior stylist and retail art director, picking up treasures wherever he went: a 1920s lacquered gold Japanese screen from a stint living in Portland, Ore.; sun-bleached sea turtle shells from a vacation in Maine. By the time the 59-year-old found his current home in 2013, a 1,000-square-foot, one-bedroom rental on the top floor of a brownstone in the Bedford-Stuyvesant neighborhood of Brooklyn, he needed a 20-foot truck to transport the goods he’d accumulated. “I wish I could be one of those people who could buy a thing, live with it, throw it out and move on,” he says. “But I can’t.”

headline.main: In Brooklyn, a Couple With Opposing Tastes Strike a Balance
